title Neth's serial core carried for real over Comlink; a real wire-vs-log-format bound found and closed
prompt Keaton asked "what could we do?" then "what do you recommend?" -- recommended wiring Neth's real Comlink carriage in place of the in-process stand-in every witness so far named, over a second simulation lap, since it proves something not yet proven rather than extending something already proven. Proceeded on that recommendation.
think read mantra's recall_sync_delivery.rye and linengrow's own mala_delivery.rye closely before writing anything, since both already establish the real hosted-carriage pattern this tree uses: localhost UDP sockets (AF_INET/SOCK_DGRAM), Comlink's shared wire_format.seal_message/open_datagram, and a source/follower pair proven both in-process (selftest) and as two real spawned subprocesses (demo). Chose to follow that exact shape rather than inventing a new one.
think picked unused ports (38494/38495) by grepping every existing *_port constant across mantra/linengrow first, rather than guessing and risking a collision with an existing delivery lab.
think designed the module to call neth_serial_core.rye's append_and_reroot completely unmodified -- the whole point of this lap is proving the already-witnessed fold behaves identically whether the record arrived in-process or over a real wire, not writing a new fold.
think built and ran the selftest immediately rather than writing the full source/follower/demo split first -- caught a real, load-bearing bound on the first run: the log's own hex line format (sig hex-encoded plus fact hex-encoded, per receipt_core.format_log_line) is comfortably under receipt_core's own 768-byte append bound, yet at 500 bytes it does not fit Comlink's wire_format.max_message ceiling (340 bytes -- wire_capacity 528 minus the sealed envelope's own header). A single Comlink hop is smaller than a single Neth log append.
think rather than shrinking the record (which would misrepresent a real Neth record) or widening Comlink's own wire capacity (which would touch a primitive every other module in this tree already relies on unmodified), looked at how mala_delivery.rye had already solved exactly this: it carries records over the wire using receipt_core's existing compact binary payload (raw signature bytes + raw fact, no hex doubling), not the log's own hex line. Reused that same encoding rather than inventing a third one, and added one new seam of my own -- reconstructing the log's hex line only on the receiving side, right before the already-witnessed append_and_reroot call, so the wire's compactness concern and the log's stable on-disk shape stay honestly separate rather than assuming one format must serve both.
think verified this fix by rerunning the selftest (GREEN, carriage-transparency proven: sealed-then-opened via the compact payload folds identically to a direct in-process call) and then the real two-subprocess demo, watching an actual UDP hop cross localhost and the follower's independently-folded root match the source's own independently-computed expectation, computed and checked before ever trusting the follower's word.
think ran all seven Neth/Mantra witnesses landed across this whole thread together at the end to confirm nothing regressed -- all seven real GREEN in one pass, including two genuinely new laps from this session (deterministic simulation, real Comlink carriage) alongside the four from earlier turns today.
obs the wire-capacity-vs-log-line finding is exactly the kind of thing a first lap "built after the real replica laps" is supposed to surface -- a real, previously-unexercised assumption (Comlink carriage "just works" for any record the log format allows) turned out false the moment it was actually tried, and the fix (separate wire and log encodings, matching precedent already in the tree) is honest rather than a workaround.
file linengrow/neth_serial_core_delivery.rye -- new; source/follower/selftest/demo over real UDP, compact binary payload on the wire, hex log line reconstructed only on receipt, feeding the unmodified append_and_reroot
file tools/neth_serial_core_delivery_witness.rish -- new; runs both the in-process selftest and the real two-subprocess demo, asserting on both
file tools/parity_ch01.rish -- wired the new witness into the living suite, directly after the deterministic simulation entry
file work-in-progress/TASKS.md -- new item naming the lap landed and confirmed GREEN, with the wire-vs-log bound named plainly rather than buried
file session-logs/20260715-150000_neth-comlink-carriage-real.bron -- this log
recommend check-in -- the Neth ladder now has a real carriage lap in addition to its four closed laps, and every Neth/Mantra witness across the whole day's thread stands real-GREEN together. This is a natural resting point: the next thing is either a genuinely different thread (per the menu offered before this recommendation), or, if staying in Neth, wiring the deterministic-simulation lap's own seeded fault injection together WITH this real carriage lap (faults over a real wire, not just an in-process schedule) -- a real third combination, not yet attempted, worth naming to Keaton rather than assuming.
